class Solution {
    public int minChanges(int n, int k) {
        int changes = 0;
        while (n != 0 && k != 0) {
            int nBit = n & 1;
            int kBit = k & 1;
            if (nBit == 1 && kBit == 0) {
                changes++;
            }
            n >>= 1;
            k >>= 1;
        }
        if (n == 0 && k == 0) {
            return changes;
        } else if (n == 0) {
            return -1;
        } else {
            while (n != 0) {
                int nBit = n & 1;
                if (nBit == 1) {
                    changes++;
                }
                n >>= 1;
            }
            return changes;
        }
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log n + log k)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution uses bitwise operations to compare the binary representations of n and k from the least significant bit to the most significant bit, counting the number of changes needed to make n equal to k. If n becomes 0 before k, it checks if k is also 0; if not, it returns -1. Otherwise, it continues counting changes for the remaining bits in n.

